---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import RelatedProducts from '../../components/RelatedProducts.astro';

const sources = [
  { source: 'Costco Customer Service (2024)', answer: '100% beef', detail: 'Confirmed in multiple customer inquiries' },
  { source: 'Kirkland Signature Product Label', answer: 'Beef only', detail: 'Ingredients list shows beef as sole meat source' },
  { source: 'USDA FSIS Records', answer: 'All-beef formulation', detail: 'No pork or poultry ingredients in formulation' },
  { source: 'Costco Annual Shareholder Meeting (2023)', answer: '100% beef', detail: 'CEO confirmed all-beef formulation' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Does Costco Hot Dog Have Pork?"
  description="Definitive answer: Costco hot dogs are 100% beef. No pork, no poultry, no fillers. Evidence and sourcing details."
  type="article"
  publishedAt="2026-04-29"
>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Does Costco Hot Dog Have Pork?</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">The definitive answer, with evidence from Costco, suppliers, and official records.</p>

    <div class="bg-green-50 border border-green-200 rounded-xl p-8 mb-8 text-center">
      <p class="text-6xl font-bold text-green-700 mb-2">No.</p>
      <p class="text-xl text-green-800">Costco hot dogs are 100% beef.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-green-600 mt-2">No pork. No poultry. No fillers. Verified across multiple sources.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">The Evidence</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-200 overflow-hidden mb-8">
      <table class="w-full">
        <thead class="bg-gray-50">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Source</th>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Answer</th>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Details</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
          {sources.map(s => (
            <tr>
              <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">{s.source}</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-3 text-green-700 font-bold">{s.answer}</td>
              <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">{s.detail}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Why the Confusion?</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Many people assume all hot dogs contain pork because pork is a common ingredient in traditional American hot dogs. Brands like Oscar Mayer, Ball Park, and even Hebrew National (Costco's former supplier) have offered pork-containing or pork-blend products.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      However, when Costco switched from Hebrew National to its own Kirkland Signature brand in 2009, it made a deliberate choice to use <strong>100% beef</strong> only. This decision simplified the supply chain and appealed to a broader customer base, including those who avoid pork for religious or dietary reasons.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
      The confusion is also fueled by Costco's <a href="/ingredients/beef-or-pork/" class="text-red-700 hover:underline">pork-related dietary information page</a>, which exists not because the hot dog contains pork, but because customers frequently ask the question.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Religious and Dietary Considerations</h2>
    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-8">
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Kosher</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">While not certified kosher, the all-beef formulation with no pork or dairy makes it acceptable for some who follow kosher-style diets. Strict kosher observers should note it's not rabbinically supervised.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Halal</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Not halal-certified, but the 100% beef formulation with no pork is compatible with halal dietary restrictions. Muslims avoiding pork can eat this product, though strict observers may prefer certified halal options.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bg-white rounded-lg border border-gray-200 p-4">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Vegetarian/Vegan</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">This product is not suitable for vegetarians or vegans. See our <a href="/hot-dog/vegan/" class="text-red-700 hover:underline">vegan alternatives guide</a> for plant-based options.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">What About the Bun?</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The bun contains <strong>no pork or meat products</strong>. However, it does contain wheat, soy, and may contain traces of milk and eggs. The full ingredient list is available on our <a href="/hot-dog/ingredients/" class="text-red-700 hover:underline">ingredients page</a>.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">The Bottom Line</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
      You can be confident that Costco hot dogs contain <strong>only beef</strong>. This has been verified by Costco directly, confirmed on product labels, and is a deliberate part of the company's supply chain strategy. If you avoid pork for religious, health, or personal reasons, the Costco hot dog is a safe choice — though always verify with your local food court if you have severe allergies or strict dietary requirements.
    </p>

    <RelatedProducts category="Food" title="All-Beef Hot Dog Alternatives" />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
